\begin_layout Section
Dycapo
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section the outcomes of the dissertation are presented.
 Dycapo is the name given to a project aiming to share knowledge and outcomes
 on dynamic carpooling.
 The information are created using a fully open and collaborative system.
 The website
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
http://dycapo.org
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is the start point and the container of each project component.
 It is a Wiki
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
MediaWiki - http://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/MediaWiki
\end_layout

\end_inset

, freely accessible and discussable.
 The Wiki content and the source code are available under permissive and
 open licenses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following are the components of Dycapo:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Research - all the theoretical knowledge summarized in Section 2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Protocol - the last draft of the protocol aiming to become a world standard
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Server - the prototype implementing dynamic carpooling functionalities and
 the protocol
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Client - will act as a start point for the clients implementing the protocol
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Protocol
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Dycapo Protocol is an open application-level protocol for enabling communication
 between dynamic (and static) carpooling servers and clients, using HTTP
 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc2616.txt
\end_layout

\end_inset

 for operations and JSON 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc4627.txt
\end_layout

\end_inset

 as data exchange format.
 It is inspired by OpenTrip Core
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
http://opentrip.info/wiki/OpenTrip_Core
\end_layout

\end_inset

, a former proposal of data exchange format for Carpooling and Dynamic Carpoolin
g presented during the MIT "Real-Time" Rideshare Research workshop
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
http://ridesharechoices.scripts.mit.edu/home/workshop/
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The protocol is released under Creative Commons Attribution-ShareAlike
 3.0 Unported license
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/legalcode
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Entities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The entities defined by OpenTrip core (using Atom Syndication
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc4287.txt
\end_layout

\end_inset

 format) have been extracted and represented using UML 2.1 Class diagrams.
 While proceeding and discussing the development of the server, those entities
 were extended and adapted.
 As discussed at the beginning of the next section, the entities were first
 encoded using XML-RPC data format, then JSON.
 The entities are represented in the Protocol using descriptive tables and
 real world code snippets.
 The Dycapo Protocol draft version of 
