 is included in the Appendix A.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following are the Models of Dycapo Protocol:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Location - represents a geographical position 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Person - a User of the system
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Trip - a single course of travel taken as part of one's duty, work, etc,
 offered by a Person.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Modality - a description about the mode of transportation being used by
 the Person offering a Trip
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Preferences - the preferences of a Driver when performing a Trip
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Participation - representing the fact of taking part in a Trip.
 Both a driver and passengers participate in a Trip.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Search - helper object to construct the complex queries related to the search
 of a Trip
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Operations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The parallel development of the server and the complexity of the entities
 involved in the protocol lent to the decision to first use XML-RPC 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
http://www.xmlrpc.com/spec
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to transport Dycapo Protocol objects in a Service-Oriented architecture.
 Moreover, it was easier for testing the application to both think and develop
 using services, therefore methods and actions.
 After reaching a considerable stable state of both the protocol definition
 and the server prototype, a switch to a complete Resource-Oriented architecture
 has been made, i.e.
 the definition of a full REST 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-1"

\end_inset

 application-level protocol.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All the operations are performed using HTTP methods GET, POST, PUT, DELETE
 
